I wasn't sure that was gonna work.

313
00:31:28,416 --> 00:31:32,407
Don't tell me that's the
first time you've done that.

314
00:31:32,509 --> 00:31:33,872
So, what kind of
return on investment

315
00:31:33,874 --> 00:31:36,566
are you getting on these drinks?

316
00:31:38,199 --> 00:31:39,861
None as pretty as you.

317
00:31:39,863 --> 00:31:42,124
Man.

318
00:31:46,883 --> 00:31:49,510
I'm Dale, by the way.

319
00:31:50,177 --> 00:31:51,739
Giselle.

320
00:32:03,188 --> 00:32:06,679
Okay, item number 44,
what do we have?

321
00:32:08,045 --> 00:32:12,303
Residency contract
for Abigail Hildreth.

322
00:32:17,229 --> 00:32:19,656
"Abigail Hildreth."

323
00:32:20,124 --> 00:32:22,152
And what's the date on that?

324
00:32:22,154 --> 00:32:25,546
Dated August 1st, 1999.

325
00:32:26,113 --> 00:32:29,372
August 1st, 1999.

326
00:32:29,374 --> 00:32:31,236
August 1st, 1999.

327
00:32:31,238 --> 00:32:35,595
And do we have the corresponding
deposition for Mrs. Hildreth?

328
00:32:35,597 --> 00:32:37,225
Yes.

329
00:32:52,566 --> 00:32:58,287
Have you ever heard the expression,
"A watched pot never boils"?

330
00:33:04,445 --> 00:33:05,873
Here it is.

331
00:33:05,875 --> 00:33:08,303
Thank you. See?

332
00:33:08,704 --> 00:33:11,763
I've got her down as item 12.

333
00:33:11,765 --> 00:33:14,725
Date of depo, September 15th.

334
00:33:14,960 --> 00:33:16,222
September 15th.

335
00:33:16,224 --> 00:33:19,216
Fifteenth of September.

336
00:33:19,319 --> 00:33:20,381
September 15th.

337
00:33:20,383 --> 00:33:22,743
Or yeah, September 15th.

338
00:33:22,745 --> 00:33:26,404
Thank you.
Okay, item number 45.

339
00:33:32,595 --> 00:33:33,292
Jimmy?

340
00:33:33,294 --> 00:33:37,517
It's my grandma. She's old.

341
00:33:37,519 --> 00:33:39,647
I'll be right back.

342
00:33:41,313 --> 00:33:41,943
Kim?

343
00:33:41,945 --> 00:33:44,172
<i>How fast can you get downtown?</i>

344
00:33:44,174 --> 00:33:45,836
Santa Fe downtown?

345
00:33:45,838 --> 00:33:47,466
<i>Albuquerque.</i>

346
00:33:47,468 --> 00:33:48,664
Why?

347
00:33:48,666 --> 00:33:50,960
I'm at the bar at Forque.

348
00:33:50,962 --> 00:33:54,320
And I've got a live one on the hook.

349
00:33:57,317 --> 00:34:00,509
I'm on my way. What's the shot?

350
00:34:00,578 --> 00:34:01,907
Definitely two or three.

351
00:34:01,909 --> 00:34:04,869
You don't think they do?
They could.

352
00:34:04,871 --> 00:34:07,531
I know, but they don't have to.

353
00:34:09,596 --> 00:34:13,553
That's possible, but I don't
understand why that's an issue.

354
00:34:13,555 --> 00:34:14,784
You can always go back.

355
00:34:14,786 --> 00:34:15,982
Yeah. Yeah.

356
00:34:18,712 --> 00:34:19,908
Viktor! There you are!

357
00:34:19,910 --> 00:34:22,238
So sorry I'm late.
I had to put out a few fires.

358
00:34:22,240 --> 00:34:23,901
No problem.
I made a new friend.

359
00:34:23,903 --> 00:34:25,565
Dale, my brother Viktor.
Hey, how you doing?

360
00:34:25,567 --> 00:34:28,593
Nice to meet you, Dale. Thanks
for keeping sis company.

361
00:34:28,595 --> 00:34:29,458
My pleasure.

362
00:34:29,460 --> 00:34:33,385
You need a drink.
Let's get you a drink.

363
00:34:34,418 --> 00:34:35,880
So, what do you do, Dale?

364
00:34:35,882 --> 00:34:37,776
I'm an engineer.

365
00:34:38,211 --> 00:34:40,438
Like Casey Jones, with the hat?

366
00:34:40,440 --> 00:34:43,766
No, idiot.
An engineer-engineer.

367
00:34:43,768 --> 00:34:45,164
Not an "engineer."
Dale builds things.

368
00:34:45,166 --> 00:34:48,491
I design things. Spillways
and drainage fields, mostly.

369
00:34:48,493 --> 00:34:50,188
I don't actually build them.

370
00:34:50,190 --> 00:34:51,052
Well, that's cool. Yeah.

371
00:34:51,054 --> 00:34:55,578
But you could still wear the hat, though.
Right? Nothing stopping you.

372
00:34:55,580 --> 00:34:56,277
Yeah, I guess I could.

373
00:34:56,279 --> 00:34:58,473
I'm just saying there's no rule
about that, as far as I know.

374
00:34:58,475 --> 00:35:01,534
You are such a brat!
Why the good mood?

375
00:35:01,536 --> 00:35:03,963
Did it go well today?

376
00:35:03,965 --> 00:35:06,126
Please tell me it went well.

377
00:35:06,128 --> 00:35:08,388
Yeah, it went well.

378
00:35:08,857 --> 00:35:11,750
Very well? Like, very, very?

379
00:35:11,752 --> 00:35:14,977
Beyond our wildest... Yeah.

380
00:35:14,979 --> 00:35:17,040
Whoo!

381
00:35:17,175 --> 00:35:19,303
How many of these has she had?

382
00:35:19,305 --> 00:35:21,499
I'm just getting started, baby!

383
00:35:21,501 --> 00:35:22,430
Remember these faces, Dale!
Giselle.

384
00:35:22,432 --> 00:35:25,158
They're gonna be on the cover of
<i>Fortune Magazine,</i> January issue.

385
00:35:25,160 --> 00:35:26,390
Giselle. Please.
Dale's a good guy.

386
00:35:26,392 --> 00:35:28,386
He's not gonna do anything.
You're boring the man.

387
00:35:28,388 --> 00:35:30,084
No, no, not really.

388
00:35:30,086 --> 00:35:31,580
Thank you.

389
00:35:31,582 --> 00:35:34,077
All right, I'm off to
the little girl's room.

390
00:35:34,079 --> 00:35:38,568
Say only nice things about me
while I'm gone, okay?

391
00:35:42,496 --> 00:35:44,691
She's something.

392
00:35:45,059 --> 00:35:46,387
Yeah.

393
00:35:48,951 --> 00:35:53,375
So, Giselle was telling me you
two are starting a business?

394
00:35:54,808 --> 00:35:56,935
What exactly did she tell you?

395
00:35:56,937 --> 00:35:59,531
Nothing much.
Just something about a dotcom.

396
00:35:59,533 --> 00:36:04,888
Some way for people to hook up with
each other using the Internet?

397
00:36:05,622 --> 00:36:07,483
Look, I'm sure
you're a nice guy,

398
00:36:07,485 --> 00:36:10,345
but she was
talking out of school.

399
00:36:11,078 --> 00:36:12,674
We're full up on this thing.

400
00:36:12,676 --> 00:36:13,239
Okay.

401
00:36:13,241 --> 00:36:16,600
We sign one more investor,
we gotta go public.

402
00:36:16,602 --> 00:36:19,728
And I'm just... No.

403
00:36:19,730 --> 00:36:23,321
We cannot take anyone else on.

404
00:36:23,323 --> 00:36:24,519
No offense.

405
00:36:24,521 --> 00:36:26,682
It's okay. Yeah.

406
00:36:29,713 --> 00:36:31,573
No worries.

407
00:37:25,713 --> 00:37:27,807
Spread your arms.

408
00:37:39,055 --> 00:37:40,550
No.

409
00:37:43,514 --> 00:37:44,776
He's got a gun.

410
00:37:44,778 --> 00:37:47,638
I don't care about the gun.

411
00:38:40,146 --> 00:38:44,703
Tomorrow, you go to
the district attorney.

412
00:38:44,705 --> 00:38:49,927
And you explain to him that
my nephew's gun was yours.

413
00:38:49,929 --> 00:38:54,818
The DA will ask you, "Why you
didn't say anything before?"

414
00:38:54,820 --> 00:38:58,312
You tell him you forgot.
You were rattled.

415
00:38:58,314 --> 00:39:01,806
Make up anything you want,
I don't give a shit.

416
00:39:01,808 --> 00:39:04,035
But it's your gun.

417
00:39:06,998 --> 00:39:08,394
Let's discuss my payment.

418
00:39:08,396 --> 00:39:12,720
That time has passed.
No $5,000 for you.

419
00:39:12,722 --> 00:39:14,216
The price is $50,000.

420
00:39:14,218 --> 00:39:17,577
How about your
payment is you get to live?

421
00:39:18,145 --> 00:39:19,541
Not enough.

422
00:39:19,543 --> 00:39:22,236
You think you can
negotiate with me?

423
00:39:22,238 --> 00:39:26,761
I say the word, my nephews
go to a certain motel.

424
00:39:26,763 --> 00:39:29,090
Pay a visit to
your daughter-in-law

425
00:39:29,092 --> 00:39:31,885
and your little granddaughter.

426
00:39:31,887 --> 00:39:34,414
What do you think happens then?

427
00:39:34,915 --> 00:39:39,106
Consider your
position carefully.

428
00:39:40,007 --> 00:39:42,134
I get my money,

429
00:39:42,136 --> 00:39:45,228
or neither of us
walk out of here.

430
00:39:54,547 --> 00:39:58,005
You're willing to die for this?

431
00:39:59,471 --> 00:40:03,761
Maybe I need the $50,000
more than you do.

432
00:40:16,707 --> 00:40:21,497
How you manage to live so
long with a mouth like that?

433
00:40:26,157 --> 00:40:28,218
$50,000.

434
00:40:29,751 --> 00:40:32,876
And the gun is yours.

435
00:41:11,876 --> 00:41:12,839
He sent you?

436
00:41:12,841 --> 00:41:14,502
I volunteered.

437
00:41:14,837 --> 00:41:17,729
Only safe way for us to talk.

438
00:41:35,068 --> 00:41:38,061
You really pushed it in there.

439
00:41:41,489 --> 00:41:43,850
That thing we did?

440
00:41:44,251 --> 00:41:47,543
He finds out, we're both dead.

441
00:41:47,545 --> 00:41:49,639
You get that, right?

442
00:41:50,074 --> 00:41:52,301
What thing we did?

443
00:41:57,461 --> 00:41:59,755
What's this? $25,000.

444
00:41:59,757 --> 00:42:01,053
What for?

445
00:42:01,055 --> 00:42:05,245
We made a deal.
I didn't hold up my end.

446
00:42:06,046 --> 00:42:10,935
Your problem is coming back
sooner than we expected.

447
00:42:27,740 --> 00:42:32,697
You gonna cash that? I might
know a guy who can help.

448
00:42:33,031 --> 00:42:35,624
It's better as a souvenir.

449
00:42:35,693 --> 00:42:39,650
I figured you'd be,
maybe, I don't know,

450
00:42:39,652 --> 00:42:41,647
a touch happier this morning.

451
00:42:41,649 --> 00:42:43,909
Maybe a smidge? Possibly?

452
00:42:43,911 --> 00:42:46,705
I am. I'm totally happy.

453
00:42:46,906 --> 00:42:49,366
Why wouldn't I be?

454
00:42:50,400 --> 00:42:52,029
I...

455
00:42:53,461 --> 00:42:56,187
I had a job offer.

456
00:42:56,290 --> 00:42:58,850
Really? From where?

457
00:42:58,852 --> 00:43:01,379
Schweikart & Cokely.

458
00:43:01,613 --> 00:43:02,443
Seriously?

459
00:43:02,445 --> 00:43:04,007
Rich Schweikart
said that they would

460
00:43:04,009 --> 00:43:06,736
even pay off my
law school loans.

461
00:43:06,738 --> 00:43:07,734
That's great!

462
00:43:07,736 --> 00:43:10,528
Please let me be there
when you tell Howard.

463
00:43:10,530 --> 00:43:12,159
Please.

464
00:43:12,261 --> 00:43:13,856
So why the sad puppy eyes?

465
00:43:13,858 --> 00:43:15,187
What, you don't want that job?

466
00:43:15,189 --> 00:43:18,015
No, no, of course I do.
I mean, who wouldn't, right?

467
00:43:18,017 --> 00:43:21,675
It's a huge firm. You get
out from under Howard's thumb.

468
00:43:21,677 --> 00:43:22,474
Right. Exactly.

469
00:43:22,476 --> 00:43:27,365
Besides, HHM is looking more and
more like a dead end for me anyway.

470
00:43:27,367 --> 00:43:30,393
Exactly. So what's the problem?

471
00:43:31,560 --> 00:43:33,322
I just...

472
00:43:38,148 --> 00:43:39,844
I don't know.

473
00:43:39,845 --> 00:43:43,670
I keep thinking of you
floating in that pool.

474
00:43:44,470 --> 00:43:48,993
You knew what you wanted,
but I got in the way.

475
00:43:49,095 --> 00:43:51,190
What are you talking about?

476
00:43:51,192 --> 00:43:55,183
You took the Davis &
Main job because of me.

477
00:43:55,185 --> 00:43:58,343
I took that job because it
was the right decision.

478
00:43:58,345 --> 00:43:59,941
A steady pay check? Done.

479
00:43:59,943 --> 00:44:04,233
A place to live that's more than,
five square feet? Boom.

480
00:44:04,235 --> 00:44:06,562
A car that's all one color?
Nailed it.

481
00:44:06,564 --> 00:44:10,721
I'm good.
I got what I wanted.

482
00:44:10,723 --> 00:44:12,318
And you?
With this Schweikart thing?

483
00:44:12,320 --> 00:44:15,080
You could have
everything you ever wanted.

484
00:44:15,082 --> 00:44:17,809
What's not to love about that?

485
00:44:19,308 --> 00:44:22,633
Yeah. What's not to love?

